rformance by a Lead Actor in a Drama Series Primetime Emmy Award winners]]\n[[Category:People from St. Louis County, Missouri]]\n[[Category:People with vitiligo]]\n[[Category:University of Texas at Austin alumni]]\n[[Category:Educators from Missouri]]\n[[Category:Male actors of German descent]]\n[[Category:Great Depression in the United States]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American actor}}\n{{Distinguish|John Ham (disambiguation){{!}}John Ham|John Hamm|Jonathan Hamm}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Jon Hamm\n| birth_name         = Jonathan Daniel Hamm\n| image              = Jon Hamm at PaleyFest 2014.jpg\n| caption            = Hamm at [[Paley Center for Media|PaleyFest]] in 2014\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date and age|1971|3|10|mf=yes}}\n| birth_place        = [[St. Louis]], [[Missouri]], U.S.\n| death_date         =\n| death_place        =\n| alma_mater         = [[University of Missouri]]\n| occupation         = {{flatlist|\n*Actor\n*Producer}}\n| years_active       = 1996\u2013present\n| partner            = [[Jennifer Westfeldt]]<br>(1997\u20132015)\n| awards             = [[List of awards and nominations received by Jon Hamm|Full list]]\n}}\n'''Jonathan Daniel Hamm'''<ref name=tvg /> (born March 10, 1971)<ref>{{cite news|title=Monitor|newspaper=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|date=March 15, 2013|issue=1250|page=23}}</ref><ref name=\"tvg\">{{cite web| url = http://www.tvguide.com/celebrities/jon-hamm/bio/190220/|title=Jon Hamm| publisher=[[TV Guide|TVGuide.com]]| archivedate= September 6, 2015| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150906064826/http://www.tvguide.com/celebrities/jon-hamm/bio/190220/}}</ref> is an American actor and producer  best known for playing advertising executive [[Don Draper]] in the [[AMC (TV channel)|AMC]] television drama series ''[[Mad Men]]'' (2007\u20132015).\n\nFor much of the mid-1990s, he lived in Los Angeles, making appearances in television series ''[[Providence (American TV series)|Providence]]'', ''[[The Division]]'', ''[[What About Brian]]'', and ''[[Related]]''. In 2000, he made his feature film debut in the space adventure film ''[[Space Cowboys]]''. The next year, he had a minor role in the independent comedy ''[[Kissing Jessica Stein]]'' (2001).\n\nHe gained wide recognition when ''[[Mad Men]]'' began in July 2007. His performance earned him the [[Golden Globe Award]] for [[Golden Globe Award for Best Actor \u2013 Television Series Drama|Best Actor in a Television Series \u2013 Drama]] in 2008 and again in 2016, and the [[Primetime Emmy Award]] for [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Lead Actor in a Drama Series|Outstanding Lead Actor in a Drama Series]] in 2015. He also directed two episodes of the show.\n\nIn 2008, Hamm appeared in a remake of the [[science fiction]] film ''[[The Day the Earth Stood Still (2008 film)|The Day the Earth Stood Still]]''. His first leading film role was in the 2010 independent thriller ''[[Stolen (2009 American film)|Stolen]]''. He then had leading roles in ''[[Million Dollar Arm]]'' (2014), ''[[Keeping Up with the Joneses (film)|Keeping Up with the Joneses]]'' (2016), and ''[[Beirut (film)|Beirut]]'' (2018), and supporting roles in  ''[[The Town (2010 film)|The Town]]'' (2010), ''[[Sucker Punch (2011 film)|Sucker Punch]]'' (2011), ''[[Bridesmaids (2011 film)|Bridesmaids]]'' (2011), ''[[Baby Driver]]'' (2017), ''[[Tag (2018 film)|Tag]]'' (2018), and ''[[Bad Times at the El Royale]]'' (2018). Hamm has received 16 [[Primetime Emmy Award]] nominations for his performances in or production of ''Mad Men'', ''[[30 Rock]]'' (2006\u20132013), and ''[[Unbreakable Kimmy Schmidt]]'' (2015\u20132019).\n\nHis other television credits include featuring in the [[Sky Arts]] series ''[[A Young Doctor's Notebook (TV series)|A Young Doctor's Notebook]]'' and guest roles in ''[[Black Mirror]]'', ''[[Parks and Recreation]]'' and ''[[Wet Hot American Summer: First Day of Camp]]''. He has also provided his voice for the animated films ''[[Shrek Forever After]]'' (2010) and ''[[Minions (film)|Minions]]'' (2015), along with the [[Legion (season 2)|second season]] of the [[FX (TV channel)|FX]] series ''[[Legion (TV series)|Legion]]'' (2018).\n\nHis most recent works include portraying the angel [[Gabriel]] in the [[Amazon Prime Video]] [[miniseries]] television adaptation of [[Terry Pratchett]] and [[Neil Gaiman]]\u2019s [[Good Omens|book]], ''[[Good Omens (TV series)|Good Omens]]''.\n\n==Early life==\nHamm was born in [[St. Louis]], [[Missouri]], the son of Deborah (Garner) Hamm and Daniel Hamm.<ref>{{cite web|title=Jon Hamm is Really Smart About Money|website=Melmagazine.com|url=https://melmagazine.com/en-us/story/jon-hamm-is-really-smart-about-money-2}}</ref> His father managed a family trucking company, and his mother was a secretary.<ref name=\"gq\">{{cite news|url=https://www.gq.com/entertainment/movies-and-tv/200811/jon-hamm-mad-men?currentPage=2 |title=Breakout: Jon Hamm |last=Martin |first=Brett |work=[[GQ]] |page=2 |date=December 2008 |accessdate=February 12, 2009 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120201175010/http://www.gq.com/entertainment/movies-and-tv/200811/jon-hamm-mad-men?currentPage=2 |archivedate=February 1, 2012 |url-status=dead |df=}}</ref><ref name=\"taking it\">{{cite journal|first=Gail|last=Pennington|title=\"Providence\" Made St. Louisan A Star, And He's Taking It From There|date=February 18, 2001|work=[[St. Louis Post-Dispatch]]|page=F5}}</ref> He is of German, English, and Irish descent; his surname came from German immigrants.<ref name=\"mad\">{{cite news|first=Megan|last=Smolenyak|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/megan-smolenyak-smolenyak/jon-hamm-genealogy_b_3039667.html|title=10 Things You Didn't Know About Jon Hamm's Roots|date=April 8, 2013|work=Huffington Post|accessdate=April 10, 2013}}</ref>\n\nHamm's parents divorced when he was two years old, and he lived in the St. Louis suburb of [[Creve Coeur, Missouri|Creve Coeur]] with his mother<ref name=\"taking it\"/> until her death from [[colon cancer]] when he was 10 years old.<ref name=\"guardian\"/> Hamm then lived with his father and grandmother in [[Normandy, Missouri]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=|title=Providence made St. Louisan a star, and he's taking it from there|last=Pennington|first=Gail|date=February 18, 2001|work=St. Louis Post-Dispatch|access-date=|page=42}}</ref>\n\nHis first acting role was as [[Winnie-the-Pooh]] in first grade.<ref name=\"handy fair\"/> At 16, he was cast as [[Judas Iscariot|Judas]] in the play ''[[Godspell]]'',<ref name=\"west201008\">{{cite news|first=Kevin|last=West|url=http://www.wmagazine.com/celebrities/2010/08/hamm_hall?printable=true|title=Jon Hamm and Rebecca Hall: Talk of ''The Town''|accessdate=July 12, 2010|date=August 2010|work=[[W (magazine)|W]]|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100716211130/http://www.wmagazine.com/celebrities/2010/08/hamm_hall?printable=true|archivedate=July 16, 2010|df=}}</ref> and enjoyed the experience, though he did not take acting seriously. He attended [[John Burroughs School]], a private school in [[Ladue, Missouri|Ladue]], where he was a member of the football, baseball, and swim teams.<ref name=\"mad1\">{{cite news|url=http://entertainment.timesonline.co.uk/tol/arts_and_entertainment/tv_and_radio/article5247450.ece|title=Mad about Mad Men's Jon Hamm|last=Armstrong|first=Stephen|date=November 30, 2008|work=The Times|accessdate=February 9, 2009|location=UK}}</ref> During this time, he dated [[Sarah Clarke]], who became an actress.<ref name=\"stein\">{{cite news|last=Stein|first=Joel|title=Hard Sell|url=http://www.menshealth.com/celebrity-fitness/hard-sell|accessdate=September 13, 2010|work=[[Men's Health (magazine)|Men's Health]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110630220519/http://www.menshealth.com/celebrity-fitness/hard-sell|archivedate=2011-06-30}}</ref> When Hamm was 20, his father died.\n\nAfter graduation in 1989 Hamm enrolled in the [[University of Texas at Austin|University of Texas]],<ref name=\"texas\">{{cite news|url=https://www.gq.com/entertainment/movies-and-tv/200811/jon-hamm-mad-men?currentPage=4 |title=Breakout: Jon Hamm |last=Martin |first=Brett |work=[[GQ]] |page=4 |accessdate=February 12, 2009 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120201192856/http://www.gq.com/entertainment/movies-and-tv/200811/jon-hamm-mad-men?currentPage=4 |archivedate=February 1, 2012 |url-status=dead |df=}}</ref> where he was a member of the Upsilon chapter of [[Sigma Nu]] fraternity. There, Hamm was arrested for participating in a [[Hazing in Greek letter organizations|violent hazing incident]] in November 1990. Mark Sanders was beaten with a paddle and a broom by other fraternity members, while Hamm led Sanders around the fraternity house with a hammer claw around Sanders' testicles; Sanders' clothes were also set afire. The incident resulted in the fraternity being shut down on campus. Hamm made a plea deal and completed probation under the terms of a [[deferred adjudication]]; the charges were dismissed during August 1995.<ref name=\"SKaplanWashPost04102015\">{{cite news|last=Kaplan|first=Sarah|date=April 10, 2015|title=Report: Jon Hamm, star of 'Mad Men,' was arrested in college for brutally hazing another student |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/morning-mix/wp/2015/04/10/report-jon-hamm-star-of-mad-men-was-arrested-in-collge-for-brutally-hazing-another-student|newspaper=[[Washington Post]]|location=[[Washington, D.C.]]|accessdate=April 10, 2015|quote=As a fraternity member at the University of Texas more than two decades ago, \"Mad Men\" star Jon Hamm was arrested in connection with a violent hazing in which a pledge was beaten, dragged by the genitals by the claw of a hammer, and had his clothes set on fire, according to the Associated Press. The actor, who was a 20-year-old sophomore at the time of the incident, was charged with a misdemeanor but made a plea deal. He received \"deferred adjudication\", the AP reported, which under Texas law allows a case to be dismissed if the defendant successfully completes probation.}}</ref><ref name=\"JFechterSAExNews04102015\">{{cite news|last=Fechter|first=Joshua|date=April 9, 2015|title='Mad Men' star Jon Hamm was charged in brutal 1990 hazing incident at University of Texas at Austin|url=http://www.mysanantonio.com/news/local/crime/article/Mad-Men-star-Jon-Hamm-involved-in-1990-hazing-6189477.php|newspaper=[[San Antonio Express-News]]|location=[[San Antonio, Texas]]|access-date=April 10, 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"PWeberAP04092015\">{{cite news|last=Weber|first=Paul J.|date=April 9, 2015|title='Mad Men' star Hamm was accused in violent fraternity hazing|url=http://bigstory.ap.org/article/0500cba41cfe452d92bd36a05d66db24/mad-men-star-hamm-was-accused-violent-fraternity-hazing|newspaper=[[Associated Press]]|location=New York|accessdate=April 10, 2015|quote=\"Mad Men\" star Jon Hamm took part in a violent college hazing in 1990 at the University of Texas that led to criminal charges and to the fraternity chapter permanently disbanding, according to court and school records obtained Thursday.}}</ref>{{rquote|right|Acting was fun, but my grandfather would always tell me, 'It's never too late to be an engineer.' You were supposed to get a 'job' and do acting on weekends or at school.|Jon Hamm<ref>{{cite journal|first=Nancy|last=Mills|title=Hamm ages well|date=July 30, 2008|work=[[Waterloo Region Record]]}}</ref>}}\n\nHamm later transferred to the [[University of Missouri]].<ref name=\"texas\"/> At Missouri he answered an advertisement from a theater company seeking players for a production of ''[[A Midsummer Night's Dream]]'', auditioned, and was cast in the production.<ref name=\"mad1\"/> Other roles followed, such as [[Leon Czolgosz]] in ''[[Assassins (musical)|Assassins]]''.<ref>{{cite web|first=Lindsay|last=Eanet|url=http://www.pastemagazine.com/articles/2010/07/watch-this-hilariously-cheesy-mizzou-recruitment-a.html|title=Watch a Hilariously Cheesy University of Missouri Recruitment Ad Featuring Jon Hamm|date=July 23, 2010|accessdate=September 4, 2012|work=[[Paste (magazine)|Paste]]}}</ref>\n\n==Acting career==\nAfter graduating in 1993 with a Bachelor of Arts degree in English,<ref>{{cite journal|first=Pete|last=Bland|title=Mad man&nbsp;\u2014 Jon Hamm's rise to becoming the slickest, suavest man on television has deep, dedicated roots in Columbia|date=July 27, 2008|work=[[Columbia Daily Tribune]]}}</ref> Hamm returned to his high school to teach eighth-grade acting.<ref name=\"taking it\"/><ref name=\"mad1\"/><ref name=\"advocate\">{{cite news|url=http://www.accessmylibrary.com/article-1G1-189051444/jon-hamm-big-gay.html|title=Big Gay Following: Jon Hamm|last=Voss|first=Brandon|date=September 9, 2008|work=[[The Advocate (LGBT magazine)|The Advocate]]|page=1|accessdate=February 12, 2009}}</ref> One of his students was [[Ellie Kemper]], who later became an actress and stars with him in the [[Netflix]] original television series, ''[[Unbreakable Kimmy Schmidt]]''.<ref>{{cite news|first=Gina|last=DiNunno|url=http://www.tvguide.com/news/ellie-kemper-hamm-1017602.aspx|title=Office's Ellie Kemper: Jon Hamm Was My \"Handsome\" High-School Acting Teacher|accessdate=August 20, 2010|date=April 21, 2010|work=[[TV Guide]]}}</ref>\n\n===Early work===\n{{rquote|right|I came in the ''Dawson's Creek'' era; it was all about tiny guys who looked like teenagers, and I haven't looked like a teenager ''ever''. So I was, like, auditioning to be their dads. At 25.|Hamm, on not finding work as a young actor{{r|postman elle}}}} Not wishing to stay in a \"normal career\", Hamm relocated to Los Angeles permanently during 1995<ref name=\"sachs201010\">{{cite news|last=Sachs |first=Adam |title=Jon Hamm: The Last Alpha Male |url=http://www.details.com/celebrities-entertainment/cover-stars/201010/mad-men-actor-alpha-male-jon-hamm?printable=true |accessdate=September 13, 2010 |work=[[Details (magazine)|Details]] |date=October 2010 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100914102210/http://www.details.com/celebrities-entertainment/cover-stars/201010/mad-men-actor-alpha-male-jon-hamm?printable=true |archivedate=September 14, 2010 |url-status=dead |df=}}</ref> with an automobile and $150.{{r|stein}} He moved into a house with four other aspiring actors and began working as a waiter while attending auditions.<ref name=\"mad1\"/> He acted in theatre, including as Flavius in a production of [[William Shakespeare|Shakespeare]]'s ''[[Timon of Athens]]'' with the [[Sacred Fools Theater Company]].<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.sacredfools.org/mainstage/98/timon/timon.htm |title= Timon of Athens |publisher= SacredFools.org |accessdate= September 22, 2016}}</ref>\n\nLooking older than his age, he found it difficult to find work as an actor, despite representation by the [[William Morris Agency]].<ref name=\"suave\">{{cite news|url=http://www.wmagazine.com/celebrities/2008/07/jon_hamm |title=Jon Hamm profile |last=Snyder |first=Gabriel |date=July 2008 |work=[[W (magazine)|W]] |page=1 |accessdate=February 10, 2009 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5n3BfLXYK?url=http://www.wmagazine.com/celebrities/2008/07/jon_hamm |archivedate=January 25, 2010 |url-status=dead |df=}}</ref>{{r|stein}}{{r|sachs201010}}{{r|postman elle}} During 1998, having failed to obtain any acting jobs after three years,{{r|gq}} he was terminated as a client by William Morris.\n\nHamm continued working as a waiter<ref name=\"mad1\"/> and, briefly, as a [[Scenic design|set designer]] for a [[softcore pornography]] movie.<ref name=\"postman elle\">{{cite news|first=Alex|last=Postman |url= http://www.elle.com/Pop-Culture/Celebrity-Spotlight/Jon-Hamm3 |title= Jon Hamm Interview |accessdate= September 21, 2010 |date= August 21, 2009 |work= [[Elle (magazine)|Elle]] |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20120614013739/http://www.elle.com/Pop-Culture/Celebrity-Spotlight/Jon-Hamm3 |archivedate= 2012-06-14}}</ref> After repeatedly failing to get promising roles, Hamm set his 30th birthday as a deadline to succeed in Hollywood,{{r|west201008}} stating: {{quote|You either suck that up and find another agent, or you go home and say you gave it a shot, but that's the end of that. The last thing I wanted to be out here was one of those actors who's 45 years old, with a tenuous grasp of their own reality, and not really working much. So I gave myself five years. I said, if I can't get it going by the time I'm 30, I'm in the wrong place. And as soon as I said that, it's like I started working right away.<ref name=\"mad1\"/>}}\n\nDuring 2000, Hamm obtained the role of romantic firefighter Burt Ridley on [[NBC]]'s drama series ''[[Providence (American TV series)|Providence]]''.<ref name=\"tcm\">{{cite web |url= http://www.tcm.com/tcmdb/person/560096%7C0/Jon-Hamm/ |title= Jon Hamm Biography |publisher= [[Turner Classic Movies]] |accessdate= February 17, 2010}}</ref><ref name=\"sun\">{{cite news |url= http://www.sun-sentinel.com/topic/env-hammqa25jan25,0,1168080.story |title= 'Mad' man Jon Hamm came out of nowhere |last= Atkin |first= Hillary |date= January 25, 2008 |work= [[South Florida Sun-Sentinel]] |accessdate= February 12, 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20090820080410/http://www.sun-sentinel.com/topic/env-hammqa25jan25,0,1168080.story |archivedate= August 20, 2009 |df=  }}</ref> His one-episode contract grew to 19,<ref name=\"taking it\"/><ref name=\"handy fair\">{{cite news |first=Bruce |last=Handy |url= http://www.vanityfair.com/online/oscars/2009/08/mad-men-qa-jon-hamm.html |title= ''Mad Men'' Q&A: Jon Hamm |accessdate= March 24, 2010 |date= August 5, 2009|work=Vanity Fair}}</ref> and enabled him to quit waiting tables.{{r|stein}}<ref name=\"suave\"/> Hamm made his feature movie debut with one line in [[Clint Eastwood]]'s space adventure ''[[Space Cowboys]]'' (2000);{{r|tcm}}<ref name=\"new york\">{{cite web|url=https://movies.nytimes.com/person/301544/Jon-Hamm/biography|title=Jon Hamm|work=The New York Times|accessdate=February 10, 2009}}</ref> more substantial roles followed in the independent comedy movie ''[[Kissing Jessica Stein]]'' (2001)<ref name=\"post\">{{cite news|url=http://www.nypost.com/pagesixmag/issues/20080803/Why+Everyones+Mad+About+Jon+Hamm|title=Why Everyone's Mad About Jon Hamm|last=Adams|first=Patty|date=August 3, 2008|work=New York Post|page=1|accessdate=February 10, 2009|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090111132646/http://www.nypost.com/pagesixmag/issues/20080803/Why+Everyones+Mad+About+Jon+Hamm|archivedate=January 11, 2009|df=}}</ref> and the war film ''[[We Were Soldiers]]'' (2002).{{r|tcm}}<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pbs.org/wnet/tavissmiley/archive/200708/20070829_hamm.html|title=Jon Hamm|last=Smiley|first=Tavis|date=August 29, 2007|work=[[The Tavis Smiley Show]]|accessdate=October 25, 2009}}</ref> During filming that movie, he turned 30.{{r|west201008}} His career was bolstered by his playing the recurring role of police inspector Nate Basso on [[Lifetime Television|Lifetime]]'s television series ''[[The Division]]'', from 2002 to 2004.<ref name=\"tcm\"/><ref name=\"sun\"/> Other minor roles followed on the television series ''[[What About Brian]]'', ''[[CSI: Miami]]'', ''[[Related]]'', ''[[Numb3rs]]'', ''[[The Unit]]'', and ''[[The Sarah Silverman Program]]''.<ref name=\"tcm\"/><ref name=\"sun\"/> Hamm's ''[[Mad Men]]'' castmate [[Eric Ladin]] has said that one of the reasons he admires Hamm is that while he \"made it\" later than most actors, Hamm never gave up on acting.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rosscarey.com/2011/04/07/episode-32-featuring-eric-ladin |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2011-05-18 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110816073646/http://www.rosscarey.com/2011/04/07/episode-32-featuring-eric-ladin/ |archivedate=2011-08-16 |df=}}</ref>\n\n===International recognition===\nHamm landed his breakthrough role during 2007, when he was cast from more than 80 candidates{{r|postman elle}} as the [[protagonist]] character [[Don Draper]], in [[AMC (TV channel)|AMC]]'s drama series ''[[Mad Men]]''. In the series, set in a fictional 1960s advertising agency, he plays a suave, married advertising executive with an obscure past.<ref name=\"parade\">{{cite news|url=http://www.parade.com/celebrity/0807/in-step-with-jon-hamm|title=In Step With... Jon Hamm|last=Brady|first=James|date=July 27, 2008|work=[[Parade (magazine)|Parade]]|accessdate=February 11, 2009}}</ref> He recalled, \"I read the script for ''Mad Men'' and I loved it.&nbsp;[...] I never thought they'd cast me\u2014- I mean, I thought they'd go with one of the five guys who look like me but are movie stars\".<ref name=\"inner\">{{cite news|url=http://www.interviewmagazine.com/film/jon-hamm/3/ |title=Jon Hamm |last=Rudd |first=Paul |work=[[Interview (magazine)|Interview]] |page=3 |accessdate=February 11, 2009 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5n3BnN6wY?url=http://www.interviewmagazine.com/film/jon-hamm/3/ |archivedate=January 25, 2010 |url-status=dead |df=}}</ref> He believes that an actor with a \"proven track record\" would likely have been chosen if another network had broadcast the show.{{r|sachs201010}} He went through numerous auditions; each time he explained to the casting directors what he could bring to the character, if given the part.<ref name=\"mad1\"/> [[Alan Taylor (director)|Alan Taylor]] and ''Mad Men'' creator [[Matthew Weiner]] initially thought Hamm was too handsome for the role but ultimately decided, \"it was perfect to cast sort of the perfect male in this part\". Weiner also sensed that the actor had suffered early loss of his parents, which was similar to Draper's [[backstory]].{{r|gq}}<ref name=\"handy200909\">{{cite news|first=Bruce|last=Handy|url=http://www.vanityfair.com/culture/features/2009/09/mad-men200909?currentPage=5|title=Don and Betty's Paradise Lost|accessdate=September 13, 2010|date=September 2009|work=Vanity Fair|page=5}}</ref> Hamm says that he used memories of his father to portray Draper,{{cn|date=April 2020}} a well-dressed, influential man of business and society{{r|handy fair}} hiding great inner turmoil{{r|gq}} and experiencing changes in the world beyond his control.\n\n[[File:Jon Hamm November 2008.jpg|thumb|left|upright|Hamm in November 2008]]\n\n''Mad Men'' debuted on July 19, 2007, with almost 1.4&nbsp;million viewers.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.usatoday.com/money/advertising/adtrack/2007-08-05-ad-track-madmen_N.htm|title=AMC uses nostalgia to draw marketers|last=Petrecca|first=Laura|date=August 5, 2007|work=USA Today|accessdate=February 11, 2009}}</ref> It developed a loyal audience, with Hamm receiving strong reviews. Robert Bianco of ''[[USA Today]]'' was complimentary of Hamm's performance, describing the actor's interpretation of Draper as a \"starmaking performance\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.usatoday.com/printedition/life/20070719/d_madmen19.art.htm|title='Mad Men': You'll buy what it's selling|last=Bianco|first=Robert|date=July 19, 2007|work=USA Today|accessdate=February 11, 2009}}</ref> ''[[The Boston Globe]]''{{'}}s Matthew Gilbert termed Hamm a \"brilliant lead\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.boston.com/ae/tv/articles/2007/12/29/surprises_from_cables_far_corners/?page=2|title=Surprises from cable's far corners|last=Gilbert|first=Matthew|date=December 29, 2007|work=The Boston Globe|page=2|accessdate=February 11, 2009}}</ref>\n\nFor his work, Hamm won the [[Golden Globe Award]] for [[Golden Globe Award for Best Actor \u2013 Television Series Drama|Best Actor in a Television Series \u2013 Drama]] during 2008.<ref name=\"globes\">{{cite web|url=http://www.goldenglobes.org/browse/member/31011|title=HFPA&nbsp;\u2014 Awards Search|work=[[Golden Globe Award]] Official Website|accessdate=February 11, 2009|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20130113114422/http://www.goldenglobes.org/browse/member/31011|archivedate=January 13, 2013|df=}}</ref> Also during 2008, he was nominated for both the [[Screen Actors Guild Award]] for [[Screen Actors Guild Award for Outstanding Performance by a Male Actor in a Drama Series|Outstanding Performance by a Male Actor]] and the [[Primetime Emmy Award]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.emmys.com/celebrities/jon-hamm |title=Jon Hamm &#124; Television Academy |website=Emmys.com |date=2015-02-13 |accessdate=2016-09-24}}</ref> for [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Lead Actor in a Drama Series|Outstanding Lead Actor in a Drama Series]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cbsnews.com/stories/2008/07/23/earlyshow/leisure/celebspot/main4286748.shtml|title=Jon Hamm Happy To Get \"Mad\" Again|date=July 23, 2008|work=[[The Early Show]]|publisher=[[CBS News]]|accessdate=February 11, 2009}}</ref> During 2009, Hamm was again nominated for the Golden Globe Award and Screen Actors Guild Award in the same category,<ref name=\"globes\"/><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/news/tv/la-en-madmen7-2009jan07,0,1776492.story|title='Mad Men' rages into award season|last=Rosen|first=Lisa|date=January 7, 2009|work=Los Angeles Times|accessdate=February 11, 2009}}</ref> and received another Primetime Emmy Award nomination for Outstanding Lead Actor in a Drama Series.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/8154102.stm|title=30 Rock leads the way for Emmys|date=July 16, 2009|publisher=BBC News |accessdate=July 16, 2009}}</ref> During 2010, Hamm received his third Golden Globe Award nomination.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/8414376.stm|title= Golden Globes 2010: the nominees|accessdate=December 15, 2009|date=December 15, 2009|publisher=BBC News}}</ref> ''Mad Men'' concluded its seven-season run on May 17, 2015.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://money.cnn.com/2015/05/17/media/mad-men-finale-plan|title='Mad Men' finale has finally arrived|accessdate=September 22, 2015|date=May 17, 2015|publisher=CNN}}</ref> Hamm received his first [[Primetime Emmy Award]] for [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Lead Actor in a Drama Series|Outstanding Lead Actor in a Drama Series]] on September 20, 2015 after receiving 12 Emmy nominations for acting for and producing the series.<ref>{{cite web|title=Jon Hamm|url=http://www.emmys.com/bios/jon-hamm|publisher=[[Academy of Television Arts & Sciences]]|accessdate=September 22, 2015}}</ref>\n\nHamm's next film role was for the 2008 science fiction movie ''[[The Day the Earth Stood Still (2008 film)|The Day the Earth Stood Still]]'', a remake of the [[The Day the Earth Stood Still (1951 film)|1951 film of the same name]].<ref>{{cite news|first=A.O.|last=Scott|url=https://movies.nytimes.com/2008/12/12/movies/12stil.html|title=It's All Over, Earthlings (Don't Flee to New Jersey)|accessdate=January 28, 2011|date=December 12, 2008|work=The New York Times}}</ref> Although the movie received mixed reviews,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.metacritic.com/movie/the-day-the-earth-stood-still|title=Day the Earth Stood Still, The (2008): Reviews|date=December 12, 2008|publisher=[[Metacritic]]|accessdate=February 11, 2009}}</ref> it was successful financially, earning $230&nbsp;million worldwide.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=daytheearthstoodstill08.htm|title=The Day the Earth Stood Still (2008)|date=December 12, 2008|publisher=[[Box Office Mojo]]|accessdate=February 11, 2009}}</ref> Hamm hosted ''[[Saturday Night Live]]'', season 34, episode 6, on October 25, 2008,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://nymag.com/daily/entertainment/2008/09/don_draper_to_host_snl.html|title=Don Draper to Host 'Saturday Night Live'|last=Brown|first=Lane|date=September 19, 2008|work=[[New York (magazine)|New York]]|accessdate=February 11, 2009}}</ref> and played various roles, including Don Draper in two sketches.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://popwatch.ew.com/2008/10/26/jon-hamm-crashe/|title=Jon Hamm crashes 'SNL'|last=Bruno|first=Mike|date=October 26, 2008|work=Entertainment Weekly|accessdate=February 11, 2009}}</ref> He returned as host again on January 30 and October 30, 2010.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://blogs.wsj.com/speakeasy/2010/01/31/saturday-night-live-the-best-skits-featuring-host-jon-hamm/|title=\"Saturday Night Live\": The Best Skits, Featuring Host Jon Hamm|accessdate=November 1, 2010|date=January 31, 2010|work=The Wall Street Journal}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|first=Mawuse|last=Ziegbe|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1651171/20101031/rihanna.jhtml|title=Rihanna, Jon Hamm Helm Halloween 'Saturday Night Live' Episode|accessdate=November 1, 2010|date=October 31, 2010|publisher=[[MTV News]]}}</ref> During 2009, Hamm guest-featured in three episodes of the [[NBC]] television situation comedy show ''[[30 Rock]]'', as [[Drew Baird]], a doctor who is a neighbor and love interest of [[Liz Lemon]]'s ([[Tina Fey]]).<ref>{{cite news|url=http://insidetv.ew.com/2009/01/21/tina-fey-and-jo/|title=Tina Fey and Jon Hamm talk about coupling up on '30 Rock'|last=Armstrong|first=Jennifer|date=January 21, 2009|work=Entertainment Weekly|accessdate=February 10, 2009}}</ref> For these performances, he received three nominations for the [[Primetime Emmy Award]] for [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Guest Actor in a Comedy Series|Outstanding Guest Actor in a Comedy Series]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.columbiatribune.com/weblogs/cool-dry-place/2009/jul/16/hamm-gets-two-emmy-nods/ |title=Hamm gets two Emmy nods |last=Bland |first=Pete |date=July 16, 2009 |work=[[Columbia Daily Tribune]] |accessdate=July 16, 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090720080429/http://www.columbiatribune.com/weblogs/cool-dry-place/2009/jul/16/hamm-gets-two-emmy-nods/ |archivedate=July 20, 2009 |df=}}</ref>\n\nHamm's first leading film role came with the independent mystery thriller ''[[Stolen (2009 drama film)|Stolen]]'' in 2009, in which he played a police officer whose son has been missing for eight years.<ref>{{cite news|first=Dave|last=McNary|url=http://www.variety.com/article/VR1118014689?refCatId=13|title=IFC pays for 'Stolen' rights|accessdate=February 15, 2010|date=February 3, 2010|work=Variety}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|first=Lindsay|last=Robertson|url=http://nymag.com/daily/entertainment/2010/02/jon_hamms_first_movie_as_a_lea.html|title=Jon Hamm's First Movie As a Leading Man, ''Stolen'', Is Finally Coming Out|accessdate=February 16, 2010|date=February 16, 2010|work=[[New York (magazine)|New York]]}}</ref> Hamm had a minor voice role in the animated feature ''[[Shrek Forever After]]''\u2014released during May 2010\u2014, as an ogre leader named Brogan.<ref name=\"brogan\"/> Also that year, he appeared as an FBI agent in the movie ''[[The Town (2010 film)|The Town]]'' (2010), with [[Ben Affleck]].<ref>{{cite news|first=Roger|last=Ebert|url=http://rogerebert.suntimes.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/20100915/REVIEWS/100919991|title=The Town|accessdate=September 17, 2010|date=September 15, 2010|work=Chicago Sun-Times}}</ref> After having received \"about 40 scripts that were all set in the 60s, or had me playing advertising guys\", Hamm was pleased that the movie offered a role \"the opposite to Don Draper\".<ref name=\"brooks20100909\">{{cite news|last=Brooks|first=Xan|title=Mad Men's Jon Hamm is the talk of The Town|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2010/sep/09/jon-hamm-the-town|accessdate=September 14, 2010|work=The Guardian |location=UK|date=September 9, 2010}}</ref> The feature received generally favorable reviews<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.metacritic.com/movie/the-town|title=The Town (2010): Reviews|accessdate=December 16, 2010|date=September 17, 2010|publisher=[[Metacritic]]}}</ref> and earned $144&nbsp;million worldwide.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=town10.htm|title=The Town (2010)|accessdate=December 16, 2010|publisher=[[Box Office Mojo]]}}</ref>\n\nHis next acting role was as defense attorney [[Jake Ehrlich]] in the independent film ''[[Howl (2010 film)|Howl]]'', based on [[Allen Ginsberg]]'s [[Howl|eponymous 1956 poem]].<ref>{{cite news|first=Ruthe|last=Stein|url=http://articles.sfgate.com/2010-09-19/entertainment/24010353_1_don-draper-jon-hamm-mad-men|title=Jon Hamm talks about playing Jake Ehrlich|accessdate=September 27, 2010|date=September 19, 2010|work=San Francisco Chronicle}}</ref> On December 12, 2010, Hamm made a guest appearance as an FBI supervisor on [[Fox Broadcasting Company|Fox]]'s animated series ''[[The Simpsons]]''.<ref>{{cite news|first=Andrea|last=Reiher|url=http://blog.zap2it.com/frominsidethebox/2010/12/jon-hamm-on-the-simpsons-i-was-considering-not-wearing-pants.html|title=Jon Hamm on 'The Simpsons': 'I was considering not wearing pants'|accessdate=December 13, 2010|date=December 11, 2010|publisher=[[Zap2it]]|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101215000920/http://blog.zap2it.com/frominsidethebox/2010/12/jon-hamm-on-the-simpsons-i-was-considering-not-wearing-pants.html|archivedate=December 15, 2010|df=}}</ref> He featured in [[Zack Snyder]]'s action-fantasy film ''[[Sucker Punch (2011 film)|Sucker Punch]]'' (2011), as the character High Roller, and the doctor.<ref>{{cite news|first=Peter|last=Travers|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/movies/reviews/sucker-punch-20110325|title=Sucker Punch|accessdate=March 25, 2011|date=March 25, 2011|work=Rolling Stone}}</ref> He also had a supporting role in the comedy ''[[Bridesmaids]]'' as [[Kristen Wiig]]'s \"rude and arrogant sex buddy\".<ref>{{cite news|first=John|last=Patterson|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2012/jun/23/jon-hamm-friends-with-kids|title=Will we get to see more of Jon Hamm's funny side?|accessdate=September 4, 2012|date=June 22, 2012|work=[[The Guardian]]}}</ref> Hamm was next seen in the independent feature ''[[Friends with Kids]]'' (2011), which he produced alongside his then-partner Jennifer Westfeldt.<ref>{{cite news|first=Kaleem|last=Aftab|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/films/features/jon-hamm--its-all-started-to-ad-up-2196314.html|title=Jon Hamm&nbsp;\u2014 It's all started to ad up...|accessdate=January 28, 2011|date=January 28, 2011|work=The Independent |location=UK}}</ref> The story concerns a group of friends whose lives are changed as the couples in the group begin to have children.\n\nHe had a recurring role in the situation comedy ''[[The Increasingly Poor Decisions of Todd Margaret]]'' in 2012, as the servant of socio-pathic billionaire Dave Mountford ([[Blake Harrison]]).<ref>{{cite news|first=Aly|last=Semigran|url=http://popwatch.ew.com/2011/12/01/jon-hamm-does-the-robot/|title=Jon Hamm pretends to be a robot. Can. Not. Compute. Awesomeness. System meltdown. Beep bop boop. \u2013 Video|accessdate=September 4, 2012|date=December 1, 2011|work=[[Entertainment Weekly]]}}</ref> Hamm hosted the [[2013 ESPY Awards|21st]] [[ESPY Award|ESPYS Awards]] on July 17, 2013.<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/espy-awards-lebron-james-tops-587825|title=Miami Heat Star LeBron James Tops ESPY Awards With Three Wins|date=July 17, 2013|work=Hollywood Reporter|accessdate=July 18, 2013}}</ref> The next year, he played sports agent [[J.B. Bernstein]] in [[Disney]]'s sports drama ''[[Million Dollar Arm]]'' (2014).<ref>{{cite news|first=Borys|last=Kit|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/jon-hamm-mad-men-million-dollar-arm-322663|title=Jon Hamm to Star in Sports Drama 'Million Dollar Arm'|accessdate=September 4, 2012|date=May 9, 2012|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]}}</ref> He co-featured with [[Daniel Radcliffe]] in ''[[A Young Doctor's Notebook (TV series)|A Young Doctor's Notebook]]'', playing an older version of Radcliffe's character, from December 2012 to December 2013.<ref>{{cite web|title=Jon Hamm and Daniel Radcliffe In 'A Young Doctor's Notebook': A Twisted Tale Worth Telling|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/maureen-ryan/jon-hamm-daniel-radcliffe-young-doctors-notebook_b_4031760.html?ir=Celebrity}}</ref> In December 2014, Hamm guest starred in a special Christmas episode of the British science fiction anthology series ''[[Black Mirror]]'', titled \"[[White Christmas (Black Mirror)|White Christmas]]\".<ref>{{cite web|last1=Wollaston|first1=Sam|title=Black Mirror: White Christmas \u2013 review: the funny, freaky, tragic near-future|url=https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2014/dec/17/black-mirror-white-christmas-great-british-bake-off|website=[[The Guardian]]|accessdate=January 20, 2018|date=December 17, 2014}}</ref> He had a number of roles during 2015, in the comedy shows ''[[Unbreakable Kimmy Schmidt]]'' and ''[[Wet Hot American Summer: First Day of Camp]]''. He was featured in the animated comedy ''[[Minions (film)|Minions]]'', as the voice of Herb Overkill.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Stern|first1=Marlow|title=Jon Hamm on His 'Unbreakable Kimmy Schmidt' Villain and Former Eighth-Grade Student Ellie Kemper|url=http://www.thedailybeast.com/articles/2015/03/23/jon-hamm-on-his-unbreakable-kimmy-schmidt-villain-and-former-eighth-grade-student-ellie-kemper.html|website=The Daily Beast|accessdate=March 11, 2016|date=March 23, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Itzkoff|first1=Dave|title='Wet Hot American Summer: First Day of Camp' Continues the Comedy on Netflix|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/07/19/arts/television/wet-hot-american-summer-first-day-of-camp-continues-the-comedy-on-netflix.html?_r=0|website=[[The New York Times]]|accessdate=March 11, 2016|date=July 15, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Fleming Jr.|first1=Mike|title=At Illumination, Jon Hamm Lends Voice To 'Minions' Movie; Tito Ortiz Returns As Executive|url=http://deadline.com/2013/04/at-illumination-jon-hamm-lends-voice-to-minions-movie-tito-ortiz-returns-as-executive-487059/|website=Deadline Hollywood|accessdate=March 11, 2016|date=April 30, 2013}}</ref> ''Minions'' was a major box office success; despite mixed reviews, it grossed a total of over $1 billion worldwide.<ref name=\"VarietyHits1Billion\">{{cite news|last1=McNary|first1=Dave|title='Minions' Hits $1 Billion at Worldwide Box Office|url=https://variety.com/2015/film/news/minions-billion-worldwide-box-office-1201580727/|accessdate=March 11, 2016|work=Variety|date=August 28, 2015}}</ref>\n\nHamm featured in the comedy ''[[Keeping Up with the Joneses (film)|Keeping Up with the Joneses]]'', alongside [[Zach Galifianakis]] and [[Gal Gadot]]; the film was filmed during the spring of 2015,<ref>{{cite web|author1=Christine|title=Extras needed for 'Keeping Up With The Joneses', starring Jon Hamm and Zach Galifianakis|url=http://www.onlocationvacations.com/2015/04/20/extras-needed-for-keeping-up-with-the-joneses-starring-jon-hamm-and-zach-galifianakis/|website=On Location Vacations|accessdate=July 18, 2016|date=April 20, 2015}}</ref> and was released during October 2016 after being delayed seven months.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Pederson|first1=Erik|title='Eddie The Eagle' Has Landed At Fox; Biopic Starring Taron Egerton, Hugh Jackman Set For 2016|url=http://deadline.com/2015/03/eddie-the-eagle-fox-taron-egerton-hugh-jackman-1201392499/|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|accessdate=July 18, 2016|date=March 13, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Lincoln|first1=Ross A.|title='Maze Runner: The Death Cure' Release Moved To 2018 As Dylan O'Brien Recovers|url=http://deadline.com/2016/05/warner-bros-maze-runner-the-death-cure-dylan-obrien-1201764118/|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|accessdate=July 18, 2016|date=May 27, 2016}}</ref> He appeared in the science fiction film ''[[Marjorie Prime]]'',<ref>{{cite web|title=First Look: Jon Hamm, Tim Robbins Have Familial Face-Off in 'Marjorie Prime' (Exclusive Photo)|url=https://www.yahoo.com/movies/first-look-jon-hamm-tim-robbins-familial-face-060000887.html|website=[[Yahoo! Movies]]|publisher=[[Yahoo!]]|accessdate=July 18, 2016|date=February 12, 2016}}</ref> which premiered at the [[2017 Sundance Film Festival]], [[Edgar Wright]]'s comedy crime film ''[[Baby Driver]]'',<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2015/film/news/baby-driver-jon-hamm-edgar-wright-1201579926/|title=Jon Hamm Joins Edgar Wright's 'Baby Driver'|date=October 20, 2015|website=Variety|last1=Kroll|first1=Justin|accessdate=July 18, 2016}}</ref> which premiered at the 2017 [[South by Southwest]] Festival, and the drama ''[[Aardvark (film)|Aardvark]]'',<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/jon-hamm-joins-zachary-quinto-842060|title=Jon Hamm Joins Zachary Quinto in 'Aardvark' (Exclusive)|last2=Kit|first2=Borys|date=December 9, 2015|website=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|last1=Ford|first1=Rebecca|accessdate=July 18, 2016}}</ref> which premiered at the 2017 [[Tribeca Film Festival]]. In 2018, Hamm appeared in the drama ''[[Nostalgia (2018 film)|Nostalgia]]'' and the political thriller ''[[Beirut (film)|Beirut]]''.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Busch|first1=Anita|title=Jon Hamm Joins Tony Gilroy's 'High Wire Act'|url=http://deadline.com/2015/05/jon-hamm-tony-gilroy-movie-high-wire-act-1201421558/|date=May 6, 2015|website=Deadline Hollywood|accessdate=July 30, 2016}}</ref>  Hamm appeared in the ''[[SpongeBob SquarePants]]'' episode \"[[Goodbye, Krabby Patty?]]\".\n\nIn 2017 Hamm joined the [[BBC]] and [[Amazon (company)|Amazon]]'s television adaptation of [[Terry Pratchett]] and [[Neil Gaiman]]'s ''[[Good Omens]]'' as the Archangel [[Gabriel]].<ref name=\"gabriel\">{{cite news |last=Lewis |first=Hillary |url= http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/jon-hamm-joins-neil-gaiman-good-omens-amazon-series-1044790 |title=Jon Hamm to Play Archangel Gabriel in Neil Gaiman's Amazon Series 'Good Omens' |work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |date=October 2, 2017 |accessdate=October 4, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\n[[File:Jon Hamm (2008).jpg|thumb|upright|Hamm, with former partner [[Jennifer Westfeldt]], at the [[60th Primetime Emmy Awards]] on September 21, 2008]]\n\nHamm was in a relationship with actress and screenwriter [[Jennifer Westfeldt]] from 1997 to 2015.<ref name=\"guardian\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2008/apr/27/television|title=The interview: Jon Hamm|last=Illey|first=Chrissy|date=April 27, 2008|work=The Guardian|location=UK|accessdate=January 26, 2009}}</ref><ref name=\"post\"/><ref name=\"people-breakup\">{{cite news|url=http://www.people.com/article/jon-hamm-jennifer-westfeldt-break-up|title=Jon Hamm and Jennifer Westfeldt Split After 18 Years Together|first=Julie|last=Jordan|work=[[People (magazine)|People]]|date=September 7, 2015|accessdate=September 7, 2015}}</ref> In an interview discussing his relationship with Westfeldt, Hamm said: \"We may not have a piece of paper that says we're husband and wife, but after 10 years, Jennifer is more than just a girlfriend. What we have is much deeper and we both know that. To me, people get married when they're ready to have kids, which I'm not ruling out.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nypost.com/pagesixmag/issues/20080803/Why+Everyones+Mad+About+Jon+Hamm?page=2|title=Why Everyone's Mad About Jon Hamm|last=Adams|first=Patty|date=August 3, 2008|work=New York Post|page=2|accessdate=February 11, 2009|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090817113216/http://www.nypost.com/pagesixmag/issues/20080803/Why+Everyones+Mad+About+Jon+Hamm?page=2|archivedate=August 17, 2009|df=}}</ref> Along with Westfeldt, Hamm has appeared in [[Gap (clothing retailer)|Gap]]-related campaign advertisements.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/11/13/business/media/13adco.html?fta=y|title=Holiday Campaigns Bring on the Humor to Reassure Consumers|last=Elliott|first=Stuart|date=November 12, 2008|work=The New York Times|accessdate=February 12, 2009|quote=The celebrities in the Gap campaign include Jon Hamm of ''Mad Men''&nbsp;... with his girlfriend, the actress Jennifer Westfeldt.}}</ref> During April 2009, Hamm and Westfeldt formed their own production company, Points West Pictures.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.latimes.com/2009/jun/03/news/en-hamm3|title=Jon Hamm's a calm 'Mad Men' guy|last=Rosen|first=Lisa|date=June 3, 2009|work=Los Angeles Times|accessdate=July 6, 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://nymag.com/daily/entertainment/2009/04/jon_hamm_and_jennifer_westfeld.html|title=Jon Hamm and Jennifer Westfeldt Fight Censorship|last=Barshad|first=Amos|date=April 27, 2009|work=[[New York (magazine)|New York]]|accessdate=May 1, 2009}}</ref> Hamm and Westfeldt are advocates of animal rescue and have adopted a mixed breed dog named Cora from the Much Love Animal Shelter in California.<ref>{{cite web | title= Mad Men Emmy Nominee Jon Hamm stays true to character, is a real lady's mans | url= http://www.animalfair.com/home/mad-men-emmy-nominee-jon-hamm-stays-true-to-character-is-a-real-ladys-man/ | publisher= [[Animal Fair (magazine)|Animal Fair]] | accessdate= September 19, 2011 | url-status=dead | archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20110925132052/http://www.animalfair.com/home/mad-men-emmy-nominee-jon-hamm-stays-true-to-character-is-a-real-ladys-man/ | archivedate= September 25, 2011 | df=  }}</ref>\n\nAlthough his role as Don Draper required Hamm to smoke, he stopped smoking when he was 24 years old.<ref name=\"snyder\">{{cite news|url=http://www.wmagazine.com/celebrities/2008/07/jon_hamm?currentPage=2 |title=Jon Hamm |last=Snyder |first=Gabriel |date=July 2008 |work=[[W (magazine)|W]] |page=2 |accessdate=February 10, 2009 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081014082058/http://www.wmagazine.com/celebrities/2008/07/jon_hamm?currentPage=2 |archivedate=October 14, 2008 |url-status=dead |df=}}</ref><ref name=\"people\">{{cite news|url=http://www.people.com/people/archive/article/0,,20060249,00.html|title=Mad About Him|last=Dodd|first=Johnny|author2=Natasha Stoynoff|date=September 10, 2007|work=[[People (magazine)|People]]|accessdate=February 13, 2009}}</ref> On set he did not smoke actual cigarettes, but rather [[herbal cigarettes]] that do not contain tobacco or nicotine.<ref name=\"people\" /><ref name=\"herbal\">{{cite news|url=http://nymag.com/daily/entertainment/2008/09/jon_hamm_on.html|title='Mad Men' Star Jon Hamm on Smoking Clove Cigarettes|last=Byrne|first=Fiona|date=September 4, 2008|work=[[New York (magazine)|New York]]|accessdate=February 12, 2009}}</ref>\n\nDuring March 2015, Hamm's representative confirmed that Hamm had recently completed inpatient treatment for [[alcoholism]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://variety.com/2015/tv/news/jon-hamm-rehab-alcohol-abuse-1201459472/|title=Jon Hamm Completes Rehab for Alcohol Abuse Before Final 'Mad Men' Premiere|date=March 24, 2015|work=Variety|accessdate=March 24, 2015}}</ref> Additionally, Hamm reported developing [[vitiligo]] during the filming of ''Mad Men''.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.theage.com.au/lifestyle/people/mad-men-stars-stress-disease-20100906-14xh2.html | location=Melbourne | work=The Age | title=Mad Men star's stress disease | date=September 6, 2010}}</ref>\n\n===Sports and related endorsements===\nHamm is an avid golfer and tennis player,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.usatoday.com/life/television/news/2007-09-26-jon-hamm_N.htm|title=A second round for 'Mad Men' star Jon Hamm|last=Clark|first=Cindy|date=September 26, 2007|work=USA Today|accessdate=February 10, 2009}}</ref> and a devoted fan of the [[National Hockey League]] (NHL) team, the [[St. Louis Blues]]; he's even appeared in two television spots advertising for the team.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://video.blues.nhl.com/videocenter/console?id=48207&catid=782|title=St. Louis Blues: Jon Hamm TV Spot|accessdate=November 6, 2009|publisher=[[St. Louis Blues]]}}</ref> He is a fan of the [[Major League Baseball]] (MLB) team the [[St. Louis Cardinals]],<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.people.com/people/article/0,,20291001,00.html|title=Jon Hamm and Jenna Fischer Hit St. Louis for All-Star Game|date=July 13, 2009|work=[[People (magazine)|People]]|accessdate=July 14, 2009}}</ref> and narrated the official highlight movie for the [[2011 World Series]], won by the Cardinals.<ref name=\"bbc\">{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/p025nr88|title=BBC Radio 5 live - Kermode and Mayo's Film Review, 29/08/2014, Jon Hamm: 'I am a cricket fan'|publisher=bbc.co.uk|accessdate=September 3, 2014}}</ref> Hamm also narrates the [[Amazon.com|Amazon]] [[National Football League|NFL]] documentary series ''All Or Nothing'' since 2015. Also, in 2012, he played in the MLB Legend and Celebrity All Star Softball game as a member of the NL. He represented the Cardinals, and hit a home run during the game.\n\n===Other product endorsements===\nDuring March 2010, [[Mercedes-Benz]] hired Hamm (replacing actor [[Richard Thomas (actor)|Richard Thomas]]) as their new voice actor for the [[Mercedes-Benz W221#S 400 Hybrid (2009-)|S400 Hybrid]] campaign.<ref>{{cite news|first=Stuart|last=Elliott|url=http://mediadecoder.blogs.nytimes.com/2010/03/03/talk-about-an-actor-getting-into-a-part-jon-hamm-is-becoming-the-commercial-voice-of-mercedes-benz/|title=Jon Hamm of 'Mad Men' Is Becoming the Voice of Mercedes-Benz|accessdate=March 3, 2010|date=March 3, 2010|work=The New York Times}}</ref> During 2013, [[American Airlines]] debuted a television commercial titled \"Change is in the Air\", featuring Hamm's voice-over. Hamm is an [[American Airlines]] frequent flier, and his ''Mad Men'' character Don Draper often spoke of aspiring to win such accounts as American Airlines.<ref>{{cite news|first=Rich|last=Thomaselli|url=http://adage.com/article/news/american-airlines-revamp-hopes-revive-travel/239264/|title=American Airlines Revamp Hopes to Revive 'Wonder of Travel'|accessdate=May 27, 2013|date=January 17, 2013|work=Advertising Age}}</ref> Hamm has also appeared in several commercials in an ongoing ad campaign for [[H&R Block]] income tax services.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bizjournals.com/kansascity/news/2017/12/26/hr-block-commercial-spokesman-jon-hamm.html|title=H&R Block brings back star for another season|last=|first=|date=|website=www.bizjournals.com|archive-url=|archive-date=|url-status=|access-date=2019-07-25}}</ref> He also appears in ongoing ads for [[SkipTheDishes]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.newswire.ca/news-releases/canadian-jon-hamm-loves-hockey-and-skipthedishes-695009621.html|title=CNW - \"Canadian\" Jon Hamm Loves Hockey and SkipTheDishes|website=www.newswire.ca}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\nInternationally considered as a [[sex symbol]], Hamm was named one of ''[[Salon.com]]''{{'}}s Sexiest Man Living in 2007<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.salon.com/entertainment/feature/2007/11/15/sexiest_man/index1.html|title=Sexiest Man Living 2007|last=Walsh|first=Joan|date=November 15, 2007|publisher=[[Salon.com]]|page=2|accessdate=February 12, 2009|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100817200116/http://www.salon.com/entertainment/feature/2007/11/15/sexiest_man/index1.html|archivedate=August 17, 2010|df=}}</ref> and one of ''[[People (magazine)|People]]'' magazine's Sexiest Men Alive in 2008.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.people.com/people/package/gallery/0,,20237714_20241212_20545197,00.html|title=2008's Sexiest Men Alive&nbsp;\u2014 Jon Hamm|date=November 19, 2008|work=[[People (magazine)|People]]|accessdate=February 13, 2009}}</ref>  During November 2008, ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'' named him one of their Entertainers of the Year.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,20240213,00.html|title=Jon Hamm: Entertainer of the Year|last=Karpel|first=Ari|date=November 14, 2008|work=Entertainment Weekly|accessdate=February 10, 2009}}</ref> He again was named one of the magazine's Entertainers of the Year during 2010.<ref>{{cite news|first=Jeff|last=Labrecque|url=http://popwatch.ew.com/2010/12/02/jon-hamm-entertainers-of-the-year/|title=Jon Hamm, Jane Lynch, and Rico Rodriguez: Our bonus Entertainers of the Year covers|accessdate=December 3, 2010|date=December 2, 2010|work=Entertainment Weekly}}</ref> Hamm also won ''[[GQ]]''{{'}}s \"International Man\" award during September 2010.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.gq-magazine.co.uk/men-of-the-year/home/winners-2010/gq-men-of-the-year-2010-winners/jon-hamm-international-man|title=Jon Hamm: International Man|accessdate=September 13, 2010|date=September 7, 2010|work=[[GQ (magazine)|GQ]]|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100924030141/http://www.gq-magazine.co.uk/men-of-the-year/home/winners-2010/gq-men-of-the-year-2010-winners/jon-hamm-international-man|archivedate=September 24, 2010|df=}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n[[File:JonHammShootingTheTown09 - Cropped.jpg|thumb|upright|Hamm on the set of ''[[The Town (2010 film)|The Town]]'' in September 2009]]\n\n===Film===\n<!-- Please note: do NOT use \"rowspans\" per WP:FILMOGRAPHY -->\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\"|Notes\n|-\n| 2000\n| ''[[Space Cowboys]]''\n| Young Pilot No. 2\n|\n|-\n| 2001\n| ''[[Kissing Jessica Stein]]''\n| Charles\n|\n|-\n| 2002\n| ''[[We Were Soldiers]]''\n| Capt. Matt Dillon\n|\n|-\n| 2006\n| ''[[Ira & Abby]]''\n| Ronnie\n|\n|-\n| 2007\n| ''[[The Ten]]''\n| Chris Knarl\n|\n|-\n| 2008\n| ''[[The Day the Earth Stood Still (2008 film)|The Day the Earth Stood Still]]''\n| Dr. Michael Granier\n|\n|-\n| 2009\n| ''[[A Single Man]]''\n| Hank Ackerley (voice)\n| Uncredited<ref>{{cite news|url=http://nymag.com/daily/entertainment/2009/12/don_draper_revealed_as_bearer.html|title=Don Draper Revealed as ''Single Man''<nowiki>'</nowiki>s Bearer of Bad News|last=Brown|first=Lane|date=December 12, 2009|work=[[New York (magazine)|New York]]|accessdate=December 14, 2009}}</ref>\n|-\n| 2009\n| ''[[Stolen (2009 drama film)|Stolen]]''\n| Tom Adkins Sr.\n|\n|-\n| 2010\n| ''[[Shrek Forever After]]''\n| Brogan (voice)<ref name=\"brogan\">{{cite news|first=Lisa|last=Rose|url=http://www.nj.com/entertainment/index.ssf/2010/03/jon_hamm_interview_from_mad_me.html|title=Jon Hamm interview: From 'Mad Men' to man of mystery|accessdate=March 10, 2010|date=March 9, 2010|work=[[The Star-Ledger]]}}</ref>\n|\n|-\n|